---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const faqs = [
	{
		q: "What exactly is the node being used for?",
		a: `A mesh node expands a decentralized, open radio network that lets people
    send text messages across the city without using cell towers or the internet. It also
    has applications in 
    <a href="https://www.gulfcoastnewsnow.com/article/meshtastic-stay-connected-hurricane-florida/65891447" 
    target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">emergency preparedness and community resilience</a> — if cell 
    service goes down, the mesh network keeps working.`,
	},
	{
		q: "What kind of equipment will be installed?",
		a: `Typically a small weatherproof enclosure (smaller than a lunchbox)
    containing simple electronics and a battery, plus a small external antenna mounted
    to a pole or bracket. The entire installation typically weighs under 1 pound.`,
	},
	{
		q: "How will it be powered?",
		a: `Most nodes are powered by a solar panel and an internal battery, however some may use 
        a standard USB power adapter plugged into an existing outlet — similar to a phone charger. If 
        no outdoor outlet is available, nodes can be solar-powered and completely self-sufficient. 
        Solar nodes require no wiring into your building at all.`,
	},
	{
		q: "What kind of antenna will be involved?",
		a: `Usually a small vertical antenna (6–12 inches tall) mounted on a mast, pole, or magnetic
    base. No drilling into your building is required — typical installation uses hose clamps
    around a mast, magnetic mounts, or non-penetrating roof mounts. Any mounting requirements
    will be discussed and agreed upon before installation.`,
	},
	{
		q: "How much maintenance is required from me?",
		a: `None. Nodes are designed to run autonomously for years. Occasionally (perhaps once or
    twice a year) a community member may request access to update firmware or check hardware.
    The terms for any access visits can be determined together and put in writing.`,
	},
	{
		q: "What frequencies does it use? Will it interfere with my Wi-Fi, TV, or other equipment?",
		a: `The Madison Mesh network operates on the 902–928 MHz ISM band — a completely different
    frequency from Wi-Fi (2.4 / 5 GHz), LTE cell service, or cable TV. Interference with
    your existing equipment is extremely unlikely. The FCC has designated this band specifically
    for unlicensed devices like this one. Transmit power is very low (typically under 1 watt).`,
	},
	{
		q: "Is any licensing required?",
		a: `No license is required for either the property owner or the node operator. The LoRa
    radio equipment operates in an unlicensed band (902–928 MHz / Part 15) under FCC rules.
    No permits or HOA approvals are needed for the radio itself, though you should check
    your own HOA or building rules before agreeing to any roof or exterior modifications.`,
	},
	{
		q: "What are the liability implications?",
		a: `The liability risk is considered extremely low, as the equipment is low-power, passive,
    and does not connect to the internet or process personal data. The installation is designed
    to leave no permanent marks and can be removed cleanly. We're happy to provide documentation
    or answer any questions your insurance provider or building manager may have.`,
	},
	{
		q: "What data does the node transmit? Is it private?",
		a: `Nodes relay short text messages and GPS position data for other users on the mesh network.
    No personal data tied to your location or identity is stored on or transmitted by the node.
    The node does not have internet access and cannot communicate with anything outside the
    local mesh network.`,
	},
	{
		q: "How long will it be there? Can I have it removed?",
		a: `That's up to you and whoever is asking to install the node. Generally, the community 
        prefers long-term hosts who can commit to keeping the node up for at least a year. If you ever 
        want the node removed, just let the community member know and they will take care of it promptly.`,
	},
	{
		q: "Who else in Madison is hosting nodes?",
		a: `The network is still growing! Current hosts include private residences across Madison,
    businesses with rooftop access, amateur radio clubs, and community organizations. We're especially 
    looking for hosts in elevated or less-covered parts of the city. Ask on Discord for current
    locations.`,
	},
	{
		q: "I'm not a tech person. Do I need to do anything to keep it running?",
		a: `No. Once installed, you do absolutely nothing. You don't need to manage software, connect
    it to your Wi-Fi, or do any ongoing maintenance. It simply powers on and runs. Our community
    members handle all technical aspects.`,
	},
];
---

<Layout
	title="Host a Node — FAQ"
	description="Thinking about hosting a Madison Mesh node on your property? Here are answers to common questions from property owners."
>
	<div class="container">
		<section class="section">
			<h1>FAQ: Hosting a Node on Your Property</h1>
			<p style="font-size: 1.1rem;">
				If someone has asked if they can place a Madison Mesh node on your property, this page covers
				everything a property owner would want to know. <strong
					>No technical knowledge required on your part.</strong
				>
			</p>
			<p>
				If you have more questions after reading this, please reach out via our
				<a href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Discord</a>
				or ask the community member who approached you.
			</p>
		</section>

		<!-- Quick benefits box -->
		<div
			class="card"
			style="background-color: oklch(22% 0.06 232.69); border-color: var(--clr-primary-darker); margin-bottom: 2rem;"
		>
			<h3 style="color: var(--clr-primary); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Why hosting helps the community</h3>
			<div
				style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 0.75rem 1.5rem;"
			>
				<div>
					<strong style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">📡 Better coverage</strong>
					<span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: oklch(75% 0.005 271);"
						>Your location may bridge a gap that helps dozens of users connect.</span
					>
				</div>
				<div>
					<strong style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">🆘 Emergency resilience</strong>
					<span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: oklch(75% 0.005 271);"
						>The mesh works when cell towers don't. Your node helps your neighbors stay connected.</span
					>
				</div>
				<div>
					<strong style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">🔧 Zero effort from you</strong>
					<span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: oklch(75% 0.005 271);"
						>Once installed, it runs silently with no action needed on your part.</span
					>
				</div>
				<div>
					<strong style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">💰 No cost to you</strong>
					<span style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: oklch(75% 0.005 271);"
						>The community member placing the node handles hardware and installation costs.</span
					>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<!-- FAQ List -->
		<section class="section">
			<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
			<div class="faq-list">
				{
					faqs.map((item, i) => (
						<div class="faq-item">
							<h3 class="faq-q">
								<span class="faq-num">{i + 1}</span>
								{item.q}
							</h3>
							<p class="faq-a" set:html={item.a} />
						</div>
					))
				}
			</div>
		</section>

		<hr class="divider" />

		<section class="section">
			<h2>Ready to host, or have more questions?</h2>
			<p>
				Join the Discord and introduce yourself in <strong>#introductions</strong> or
				<strong>#general</strong>. Community members can answer specific questions about your location and
				coordinate an installation visit at your convenience.
			</p>
			<div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.75rem;">
				<a
					href="https://discord.gg/fd3JUZc2CN"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noopener noreferrer"
					class="btn btn-primary"
				>
					Join the Discord &rarr;
				</a>
				<a href="/getting-started" class="btn btn-secondary"> Learn more about the network </a>
			</div>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>

<style>
	.faq-list {
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		gap: 0;
	}

	.faq-item {
		padding: 1.5rem 0;
		border-bottom: 1px solid var(--clr-neutral-border);
	}

	.faq-item:last-child {
		border-bottom: none;
	}

	.faq-q {
		display: flex;
		align-items: baseline;
		gap: 0.75rem;
		font-size: 1.05rem;
		color: var(--clr-primary);
		margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
		font-weight: 600;
	}

	.faq-num {
		flex-shrink: 0;
		min-width: 1.6rem;
		height: 1.6rem;
		background-color: var(--clr-primary);
		color: var(--clr-neutral);
		border-radius: 50%;
		font-size: 0.8rem;
		font-weight: 700;
		display: inline-flex;
		align-items: center;
		justify-content: center;
	}

	.faq-a {
		margin: 0;
		padding-left: 2.35rem;
		color: var(--clr-light);
		font-size: 0.97rem;
		line-height: 1.65;
	}
</style>
